          "logprobs": [],
          "text": "Research indicates that increased frequency of substance use can negatively impact access to mental health treatment. A study published in *Psychiatric Services* found that individuals with substance use disorders alone had higher rates of emergency department utilization but not of other forms of health care use, suggesting that increased substance use may lead to decreased access to comprehensive mental health services. ([psychiatryonline.org](https://psychiatryonline.org/doi/10.1176/appi.ps.20220491?utm_source=openai))\n\nAdditionally, the separation of substance use disorder treatment from general health care has created barriers to accessing mental health services. The *Facing Addiction in America* report highlights that this division has been costly and often harmful, reinforcing the notion that substance use disorders are different from other medical conditions and limiting access to comprehensive mental health care. ([ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK424848/?utm_source=openai))\n\nThese findings suggest that increased substance use can lead to decreased access to mental health treatment, emphasizing the need for integrated care approaches to address both substance use and mental health disorders effectively. "
