          "text": "A reanalysis of a meta-analytic study on peer influence suggests that the observed effects may be distorted due to methodological issues, such as correlations with measurement errors and regression toward the mean, rather than indicating a true causal relationship. The authors caution that proving causal effects of peer influence through observational data is challenging and may not be feasible. ([pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov](https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37954301/?utm_source=openai))\n\nAdditionally, research highlights the difficulty in distinguishing between homophily (the tendency to associate with similar others) and social contagion (peer influence) in observational studies. This confounding makes it hard to establish a causal link between peer behavior and individual substance use. ([arxiv.org](https://arxiv.org/abs/1004.4704?utm_source=openai))\n\nThese findings underscore the complexities in attributing changes in substance use frequency directly to peer influence, suggesting that observed associations may not reflect a causal relationship. "
